
ST-T1024 v1.4

A Tile-Based Deterministic Inference Architecture
with Fuzzy Routing and Hybrid FSM–Transformer 
Execution for Energy-Constrained AI Systems



Abstract
ST-T1024 is a modular inference architecture designed for energy-constrained AI systems. The
proposal partitions computation into independent tiles, activates only one tile per query, uses a
Fuzzy Inference System (FIS) for routing, and combines Finite State Machines (FSMs) with tiny
transformers inside each tile.



1. Introduction
The central motivation is the Energy Constraint Hypothesis: future AI capability may be constrained
by energy availability, memory movement, and infrastructure costs. ST-T1024 attempts to reduce
the active computational footprint per query.



2. Architecture
The architecture consists of N independent tiles. Only one tile is intended to be active for a given
query, thereby reducing active silicon, memory accesses, and communication overhead.



3. FIS Routing Layer
A Fuzzy Inference System computes membership scores for each tile domain. The tile with the
highest score is selected for execution.



4. FSM–Tiny Transformer Tile
Each tile contains an FSM controller, domain knowledge, local memory resources, and a
lightweight transformer. The FSM provides deterministic orchestration while the transformer
performs localized inference.



5. Energy Model
Symbolically: E_total = E_compute + E_memory + E_routing + E_idle. The proposal seeks to
minimize the active energy expenditure associated with each query.



6. WCET Considerations
Worst-Case Execution Time constraints can be defined at tile level, supporting deterministic
deployment scenarios.



7. Potential Role in Surviving the Energy Wall
If future AI systems become increasingly constrained by energy consumption, sparse activation
strategies may offer one possible path toward improved efficiency. ST-T1024 is presented as a
conceptual architecture in that direction.


8. Limitations
Routing overhead, domain partitioning challenges, memory duplication, cross-domain reasoning,
and hardware implementation complexity remain important open questions.



9. Related Work
Relevant areas include Mixture-of-Experts architectures, sparse neural networks, quantized
networks, fuzzy control systems, and deterministic real-time systems.


